      '<div>\n    <h2>Internet-based treatment</h2>\n    There is good support that psychological treatment, especially Cognitive Behavioural Therapy, can be effectively delivered digitally in the treatment of a number of mental health problems (Andrews et al, 2018). In their literature review and meta-analysis from 2018, Andrews et al concluded that internet-based Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (iCBT in English) for anxiety and depressive disorders is effective, acceptable and practical health care. When compared directly, iCBT has been shown to be as effective as face-to-face Cognitive Behavioural Therapy, and with additional benefits in terms of privacy and availability of treatment (Anderson et al, 2014).\n\n    As with all types of treatment, there is no one-size-fits-all model. Braive does not believe or believe that internet-based treatment programs are the best solution for all clients. \n\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h2>Behavioral Therapy</h2>\n    Braive\'s programs are primarily based on Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT), but include components of third-generation cognitive therapies, such as mindfulness (Goldberg et al., 2018), metacognitive therapy (Wells & King, 2006), and Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT) (Hayes, 2004; Roemer & Orsillo, 2007). \n    Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) is one of the best-documented therapies for a range of mental disorders (Butler et al, 2006), and CBT is considered an evidence-based treatment for depression, generalized anxiety, post-traumatic stress disorder, panic disorder, social anxiety, eating disorders, obsessive-compulsive disorder, as well as several other mental and medical conditions (Up to date, 2018). According to the underlying principles of CBT, psychopathology, or emotional disorders, are the result of cognitive disorders and maladaptive behaviours (Beck, 1976). Most CBT-based programs present a treatment model that consists of learning techniques and strategies to reduce maladaptive thoughts, feelings, and behaviours that characterize or perpetuate symptoms of the mental disorder. CBT often includes psychoeducation, challenging unhelpful beliefs and errors in thinking, relaxation techniques, behavioural activation, coping strategy exploration, exposure, stress management skills, and/or assertiveness training etc (Beck, 2011).\n\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h2>Components</h2>\n    <h3>Analysis Evidence for general components of the programs:</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <b>Psychoeducation:</b> All programs contain psychoeducation via audio-video or text. Psychoeducation is an important component of CBT, and psychoeducation alone has been shown to reduce symptoms of anxiety and depression (Donker et al., 2009). The purpose of psychoeducation is to improve the person\'s understanding of psychological processes through an explanation of symptoms and techniques for challenging unhelpful beliefs, actions, and judgment. The persona videos in the various programs also contain psychoeducation about symptoms that are conveyed through examples that the various target groups can recognize themselves in. \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Cognitive restructuring:</b> Cognitive therapy, with a focus on challenging thought content, and creating alternative thoughts and changing beliefs, has shown significant improvement in symptoms of anxiety and depression, which are maintained after two years (Newman, 2002). \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Concern and pondering:</b> CBT with components such as behavioural activation, selective attention, interpersonal skills (assertiveness) as well as mindfulness and metacognitive therapy has been shown to reduce brooding and worry, which is considered a key component in anxiety and depression (Nolen-Hoeksema et al., 2008; Querstres & Cropley, 2013). The components that address worry and anxiety are adapted from metacognitive therapy (Wells, 2011) and rumination-focused cognitive behavioural therapy (Watkins, 2016). \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Assertive communication (Assertiveness):</b> Assertiveness has been shown to be a relevant factor for various mental disorders, and thus a transdiagnostic intervention. Training of skills related to assertiveness is associated with increasing self-assertive behaviour, reducing symptoms of depression and anxiety, and increasing self-esteem and satisfaction in relationships (Speed ​​et al., 2018).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Inner dialogue / cognitive diamond:</b> The observation model in the programs is based on the ABC model (Ellis, 1957), and sorts thoughts, reactions, emotions and actions in a situation. This is to more easily see how the different components affect each other. \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Diary / writing exercises:</b> expressive writing helps to make it easier to process one\'s feelings as the patient gets to write about their thoughts, feelings and things they are worried about (Pennebaker & Chung, 2007). The method has been shown to improve emotional and physical health (Baikie & Wilhelm, 2005) and provide better conditions for good sleep (Harvey & Farrell, 2003; Mooney, Espie & Broomfield, 2009). \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Relapse prevention:</b> For many, mental illness follows a course of improvement followed by relapse (Goldberg & Goodier, 2005), and focus on the prevention of new episodes is, therefore, a key and crucial component in the final part of treatment. Relapse is particularly relevant for depression (Kessing et al., 2004). For sleep, the user learns to identify so-called high-risk situations at the same time as establishing strategies for how to deal with thoughts and behaviour when experiencing poor sleep (Thorndike et al., 2008).  \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Heart rate variability (HRV):</b> HRV training for a group of employees with high blood pressure showed a significant reduction in blood pressure, stress, symptoms of depression and better emotional health (McCraty et al., 2003).\n    </ul>\n\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h3>Evidence for components related to treatment of depression:</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <b>Behavioural activation:</b> Mertell, Dimidjian and Herman-Dunn (2010) describe the most central principles in behavioural activation and point out how to change the person\'s emotions by helping them change what they do. Behavioural activation has been studied alone and in combination with CAT in several studies, e.g. Jacobsen et al (1996); Dimidjian et al. (2006). It alone has been shown to be a useful method of reducing the symptoms of depression. \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            A recent meta-analysis (Hoffman et al, 2017) that included 24 studies showed that treatment of depression with CBT is associated with moderate improvement in quality of life. \n        </li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h3>Evidence of components) related to anxiety treatment:</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <b>Interoceptive exposure:</b> Pompoli et al (2018) conducted a systematic literature review and meta-analysis of components for the treatment of panic disorder. Exposure was the single component that had the greatest effect on reducing symptoms. Interoceptive exposure is an effective method of reducing this (Dixon et al., 2015).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Changing disaster thoughts and misinterpretations:</b> A cognitive model that focuses on changing disaster thoughts has been shown to reduce symptoms, provide fewer panic attacks and less avoidance behaviors (Teachman et al., 2010).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Safety behaviours in social situations:</b> Safety behaviours is a central part of perpetuating and increasing the symptoms of social anxiety. People with social anxiety often experience increased anxiety reactions related to specific experiences and choose to use safety behaviours to manage these symptoms. Addressing and challenging these safety behaviours have been shown to be important to improvement in the treatment of social anxiety (Clark, 2005). \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Exposure to dreaded situations:</b> Exposure and behavioural experiments can be used in many different contexts to test how correct the patient\'s assumptions and hypotheses about different situations are (Bennett-Levy, 2004). It is an effective treatment component for social anxiety (Wells et al., 2016).\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h3>Evidence for components related to the treatment of generalized anxiety disorder:</h3>\n    Clinical studies have shown that cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) is an effective treatment for generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) compared to control groups and other psychotherapies, with effective treatment components such as relaxation training, conscious presence (including meditation/mindfulness, selective attention and progressive muscle relaxation), cognitive restructuring and exposure with response prevention (Craske et al. 2019). A combination of cognitive therapy, mindfulness and ACT (Acceptance and Commitment Therapy) in the treatment of GAD has previously been researched by Roemer & Orsillo (2007) with a significant reduction in diagnosis-specific symptoms and depressive symptoms, as well as increased reporting of own quality of life. Metacognitive treatment with a focus on second-degree anxiety, which differs from type 1 and type 2 anxiety thoughts, has shown a good effect in the short term and when evaluated one year later (Wells & King, 2006; Normann et al., 2014).\n\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h3>Evidence for components related to the treatment of stress:</h3>\n    Cognitive-behavioural therapy has been shown to reduce stress among non-clinical populations, such as health professionals (Ruotsalainen et al., 2015).\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <b>Conflict management:</b> Training in empathic communication at work has been shown to reduce distress and prevent increased work-related stressors (Wacker & Dziobek, 2018).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Static and dynamic mindset (Growth and fixed mindset):</b> Compounds related to static and dynamic mindset is based on Carol Dweck research ((1999; 2008). \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Values (ACT):</b> Tasks relating to values are based on the \'Bull\'s Eye Values\' and helps the user to identify and evaluate personal values (Lundgren et al., 2012).\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h3>Evidence for components related to the treatment of sleep disorders:</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <b>Sleep:</b> According to a large literature review, internet-based CBT for insomnia has shown a good effect on sleep disorders (Riemann et al., 2017). The same report shows that the method also in cases with comorbidity has an effect on both anxiety and depression symptoms. Two relatively new studies show that CBT for sleep problems via the internet leads to an improvement in several aspects of our daily lives, in addition to symptoms of anxiety, depression and fatigue as well as health-related quality of life (Espie et al., 2018; Freeman et al., 2017 ), also over time (Batterham et al., 2017)\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Screening - Insomnia Severity Index:</b> A validated sleep test that contains seven questions about sleep where the result gives the degree of sleep problem in four levels (ISI; Bastien, Vallières, Morin & 2001).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Sleep diary:</b> Because sleep diaries have shown high reliability and low recall bias, it is a good and reliable tool for measuring sleep and its development over time (Bolger, Davis & Rafaeli, 2003; Libman et al., 2000). In addition, changes in sleep patterns can be linked to the various activities and lifestyle changes the user tries during the program. \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Psychoeducation - sleep physiology:</b> daily rhythm, sleep pressure, normal sleep, etc. (Borbély, 1982) \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Psychoeducation - sleep hygiene:</b> daily routines and environmental factors (Stepanski & Wyatt, 2003)\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Sleep restriction:</b> a validated and effective method (Miller et al., 2014) where the intention is to improve sleep efficiency by reducing time spent in bed to match sleep time (Morin et al., 2006).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Stimulus control:</b> an important part of a sleep treatment program where the goal is to reduce the anxiety and restlessness associated with bed through various behavioural strategies, as well as to establish a regular sleep schedule (Bootzin, 1972; Bootzin, 1979). In Braive\'s program, they are about psychoeducation and activity planning. \n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Cognitive strategies:</b> psychological methods used to identify, challenge and change misconceptions about sleep problems and their consequences (Morin & Espie, 2004).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Relaxation exercises:</b> have shown a positive effect in CAT-based programs for sleep in, among other things, difficulty falling asleep (Waters et al., 2003).\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h3>Evidence for components related to mindfulness and relaxation:</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n            <b>Progressive muscle relaxation:</b> Relaxation exercises, such as progressive muscle relaxation, are used as an effective treatment component to reduce anxiety and muscle tension (Manzoni et al., 2008).\n        </li>\n        <li>\n            <b>Mindfulness:</b> Goldberg et al (2018) recently collected evidence from 142 RCTs that included mindfulness-based interventions for mental disorders. Mindfulness showed superior effect compared with both active control groups and those who did not receive treatment. Depression was among the patient groups that showed the best effect. According to a literature review, mindfulness has shown a positive effect in sleep treatment (Creswell, 2017). The components have been developed in collaboration with Mark Anderson (PhD). Mindfulness has also been shown to be a useful tool for non-clinical populations (Khoury et al., 2015).\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <h2>References</h2>\n    Andersson, G., Cuijpers, P., Carlbring, P., Riper, H., & Hedman, E. (2014). Guided Internet ‐ based vs. face ‐ to ‐ face cognitive behavior therapy for psychiatric and somatic disorders: a systematic review and meta ‐ analysis. World Psychiatry, 13 (3), 288-295.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Andrews, G., Basu, A., Cuijpers, P., Craske, MG, McEvoy, P., English, CL, & Newby, JM (2018). Computer therapy for the anxiety and depression disorders is effective, acceptable and practical health care: an updated meta-analysis. Journal of anxiety disorders.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Baikie, K., & Wilhelm, K. (2005). Emotional and physical health benefits of expressive writing. Advances in Psychiatric Treatment, 11 (5), 338-346. doi: 10.1192 / apt.11.5.338\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Bastien CH, Vallières A, Morin CM (2001) Validation of the insomnia severity index as an outcome measure for insomnia research. Sleep Med 2: 297–307.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Bastien CH, Vallières A, Morin CM (2001) Validation of the insomnia severity index as an outcome measure for insomnia research. Sleep Med 2: 297–307.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Batterham PJ, Christensen H, Mackinnon AJ, Gosling JA, Thorndike FP, Ritterband LM, Glozier NG, Griffiths KM. Trajectories of change and long-term outcomes in a randomized controlled trial of internet-based insomnia treatment to prevent depression. BJPsych Open. 2017 Sep; 3 (5): 228–235. doi: 10.1192 / bjpo.bp.117.005231\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Beck, AT (1976). Cognitive therapy and the emotional disorders. New York: International Universities Press\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Beck JS. (2011) Cognitive Behavior Therapy: Basics and Beyond, 2nd ed, Guilford Press, New York. p.391.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Bennett-Levy, JE, Butler, GE, Fennell, ME, Hackman, AE, Mueller, ME, & Westbrook, DE (2004). Oxford guide to behavioral experiments in cognitive therapy. Oxford University Press.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Bolger N, Davis A, Rafaeli E. Diary methods: Capturing Life as it is Lived. Annu Rev Psychol. 2003; 54: 579-616. \t\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Borbély A. Sleep regulation: circadian rhythm and homeostasis. In: Ganten D, Pfaff D, eds. Sleep. Clinical and experimental aspects. Berlin: Springer Verlag, 1982: 83-104. \t\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Butler, AC, Chapman, JE, Forman, EM, & Beck, AT (2006). The empirical status of cognitive-behavioral therapy: a review of meta-analyzes. Clinical Psychology Review, 26 (1), 17-31.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Clark, DM (2005). A cognitive perspective on social phobia. The essential handbook of social anxiety for clinicians, 193-218.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Creswell JD. Mindfulness Interventions. Annu Rev Psychol. 2017; 68: 491-516. \n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Dimidjian, S., Hollon, SD, Dobson, KS, Schmaling, KB, Kohlenberg, RJ, Addis, ME, ... & Atkins, DC (2006). Randomized trial of behavioral activation, cognitive therapy, and antidepressant medication in the acute treatment of adults with major depression. Journal of consulting and clinical psychology, 74 (4), 658.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Dixon, LJ, Kemp, JJ, Farrell, NR, Blakey, SM, & Deacon, BJ (2015). Interoceptive exposure exercises for social anxiety. Journal of Anxiety Disorders, 33, 25-34.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Donker, T., Griffiths, KM, Cuijpers, P., & Christensen, H. (2009). Psychoeducation for depression, anxiety and psychological distress: a meta-analysis. BMC medicine, 7 (1), 79.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Dweck, CS (2008). Mindset: The new psychology of success. Random House Digital, Inc.\n    